d"},"en":{"Abt 1170–1228":"about 1170–1228","1168–1203":"1168–1203","1170–1228":"1170–1228","1171–1243":"1171–1243","1217–1251":"1217–1251","1145–1189":"1145–1189","1145–Female":"1145–Deceased","1251":"1251","About 1189":"about 1189","1171":"1171","1170":"1170","abt 1168":"about 1168","1217":"1217","1228":"1228","1215":"1215","1203":"1203","1224":"1224","1168":"1168","about 1226":"about 1226","1189":"1189","1145":"1145","1243":"1243","Abt 1170":"about 1170","1208":"1208","1219":"1219","1207":"1207","Ingoldisthorpe, Norfolk, England":"Ingoldisthorpe, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","Raynham Hall, West Raynham, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom":"West Raynham, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","West Raynham, Norfolk, England":"West Raynham, Norfolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":45,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":54,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas de Ingoldisthorpe I was born about 1170, in Ingoldisthorpe, Norfolk, England, his father, Alan de Ingoldisthorpe, was 27 and his mother, Unknown de Sharnebarne, was 27. He married Joan de Beauffou. They were the parents of at least 1 son. In 1225, at the age of 58, his occupation is listed as sheriff of norfolk and suffolk in or about the 8th or 9th of king henry iii. He died in 1228, in West Raynham, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 59."},"et":{"Abt 1170–1228":"umbes 1170–1228","1168–1203":"1168–1203","1170–1228":"1170–1228","1171–1243":"1171–1243","1217–1251":"1217–1251","1145–1189":"1145–1189","1145–Female":"1145–Surnud","1251":"1251","About 1189":"umbes 1189","1171":"1171","1170":"1170","abt 1168":"umbes 1168","1217":"1217","1228":"1228","1215":"1215","1203":"1203","1224":"1224","1168":"1168","about 1226":"umbes 1226","1189":"1189","1145":"1145","1243":"1243","Abt 1170":"umbes 1170","1208":"1208","1219":"1219","1207":"1207","Ingoldisthorpe, Norfolk, England":"Ingoldisthorpe, Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Raynham Hall, West Raynham, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom":"West Raynham, Norfolk, Inglismaa